<a id="comment-3508"></a>
  <div class="comment styledbox">
    <h3 class="title"><a href="/articles/diylighting#comment-3508" class="active">tinted glass instead of blue bulb</a></h3>
    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="http://www.modernfuroshiki.com">jjozsi</a> (not verified) on Fri, 2009-07-03 22:01.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>Hi,<br />
I had the same problem, finding the blue tinted bulb was impossible (in Ireland and UK).<br />
So since I worked for a stained glass company I had a good knowledge on different coloured glasses.</p>
<p>MY SOLUTION:<br />
dark blue water glass (that's the name of the glass, you can get it at the nearest stained glass workshop)</p>
<p>It is thin, and cracks from the heat but I sliced it up to four pieces and this way it stands the heat.<br />
You can also get it toughened (tempered) but it's expensive.</p>
<p>The result is bright white light (although the blue glass shades the light a little)</p>
</div>
    <div class="links"><a href="/comment/reply/19/3508">reply</a></div>
